covery was against chat-74's stalled staging-and-M2, not against this lesson). Lesson body region read (head-200 + view_range 200–500): standard chat-39 TBD scaffold confirmed in place at end-of-file with full-stem h2 id `practice-exercise-build-genres-puzzle` (per the established `practice-exercise-build-{full-stem}` pattern), 3 quiz-question divs each with B-correct shape-1 attributes (`data-correct="false"`/`data-correct="true"` — to be flipped to shape-2 outer-single-quotes per chat-57-close codification at M1), literal U+2014 em-dash codepoint already present in scaffold's 'Objective: TBD — to be filled in chat 40+.' line confirming continued retrieval-discipline alignment. Lesson covers FIVE distinct puzzle sub-genres in a single interactive demo: Match-3 (8×8 gem grid with 6 colors, click-to-select-then-swap with one-step adjacency check, no cascade in JS demo despite description mentioning combos), Sliding-puzzles (4×4 with 1–15 + 0-empty, 100-iteration random-walk shuffle with valid-move constraint, `checkWin()` linear scan), Physics-puzzles (projectile with gravity, click-to-aim launch, 3 randomly-placed targets with circle-distance hit detection), Pattern-memory (Simon-style 4-button color sequence with progressive-length growth on success and reset on miss), and Logic-gates (3 boolean inputs A/B/C, AND-gate output, click-to-toggle). The unifying architecture is an explicit polymorphic-dispatch pattern: `PuzzleGame.puzzles = {match3: new Match3Puzzle, sliding: new SlidingPuzzle, physics: new PhysicsPuzzle, pattern: new PatternPuzzle, logic: new LogicPuzzle}` dict + uniform `init()/handleClick(mx,my)/update()/render()/hint()/shuffle()` interface across all five classes; the controller's `handleClick(e)`, `gameLoop()`, `reset()`, `hint()`, `shuffle()` methods all dispatch via `this.puzzles[this.currentPuzzle].method(...)` without ever branching on `currentPuzzle` value — the dict-index IS the polymorphic dispatch. Lesson then covers Best Practices (Clear Rules / Progressive Difficulty / Visual Feedback / No Dead Ends / Hint Systems / Satisfying Effects / Multiple Solutions / Undo Feature) and Key Takeaways (8 emoji-bulleted items including procedural-generation-for-replayability). **M1 pick — three orthogonal axes confirmed after lesson body read, with delta noted from chat-75 brief pre-read hypotheses:** (a) **Polymorphic puzzle-genre dispatch at PUZZLE-GENRE scope** — the lesson's central architectural pattern with `puzzles = {match3, sliding, physics, pattern, logic}` dict + uniform `init()/handleClick()/update()/render()` interface; adding a sixth genre (e.g., word puzzles per the lesson's mentioned-but-not-implemented sixth) = one new class + one dict entry, zero changes to controller dispatch code; Open/Closed Principle satisfied at PUZZLE-GENRE scope; same UIManager-polymorphic-dispatch pattern from chat-67 graphics_ui_hud + same PlatformAdapter pattern from chat-73 publishing_platforms applied at PUZZLE-GENRE scope = SECOND lesson reinforcing the polymorphic-dispatch-via-shared-protocol pattern at a new domain scope (after chat-73's PLATFORM-API scope), FIRST applied at PUZZLE-GENRE scope. **(This axis REPLACES the chat-75 brief's pre-read hypothesis (a) BOARD-REPRESENTATION-vs-OOP-cells which was too narrow — the lesson's lead architectural idea is the 5-genre uniform interface, not the inside-match-3 grid-vs-cell debate.)** (b) **Grid-state-as-2D-array at BOARD-REPRESENTATION scope** — match-3 uses `grid[y][x] = color_int` (8×8, ints 0–5) and sliding uses `grid[y][x] = number` (4×4, ints 0–15 with 0 = empty); the 2D-array shape is shared between the two grid-based puzzle genres and is dramatically simpler to clone (for undo), serialize (for save), pass to detection algorithms (match-finding) and compare (for win-check) than a parallel `Cell` object graph would be; same data-driven externalization pattern as architecture_save_load schema chat-58 + pathfinding terrain-cost dict chat-60 + behavior-trees child-list-order chat-61 + decision-making personality dict chat-62 + procedural generation seed chat-68 + publishing_executables .spec file chat-70 + publishing_marketing pitch templates chat-71 + publishing_performance algorithmic-axis toggles chat-72 + publishing_platforms TARGETS+ADAPTERS dicts chat-73 + publishing_updates CADENCES dict chat-74 applied at BOARD-REPRESENTATION scope = SEVENTEENTH lesson reinforcing data-driven externalization across Phase 8, FIRST applied at BOARD-REPRESENTATION scope where the board IS the data the puzzle's algorithms (swap, slide, match-detect, cascade) read and mutate. **(This axis TAKES the chat-75 brief's pre-read hypothesis (a) at the new (b) slot.)** (c) **Match-cascade-as-fixed-point-loop at MATCH-CASCADE scope** — match-3's full mechanic (mentioned in lesson description but not implemented in JS demo) is `while step(): combo += 1` where each `step()` does {detect matches → clear matched cells → apply gravity dropping remaining tiles → spawn new tiles from top → return True if any change happened, False if state stabilized}; same fixed-point-iteration shape as chat-74 publishing_updates' MIGRATIONS chain (each iteration is a frozen contract that may produce a new state requiring another iteration) applied at MATCH-CASCADE scope, with combo multiplier as natural by-product of iteration count; folds the brief's pre-read hypothesis (b) MATCH-DETECTION (flood-fill vs nested-loop) INTO this axis as one component of the per-iteration step rather than promoting it to its own axis (BOARD-REP at (b) and MATCH-CASCADE at (c) are more orthogonal as a pair than MATCH-DETECTION vs CASCADE would be — the latter pair both live inside the cascade step). **(This axis MATCHES the chat-75 brief's pre-read hypothesis (c).)** Cross-references chat-58 architecture_save_load (schema-as-frozen-contract carry-forward applied to BOARD-REPRESENTATION scope at axis (b): a 2D `board[row][col] = color_int` array IS a frozen data contract that match-detection