ry event routed through `PUZZLES[active].handle_click(...)` — 'match3 swap (3,2)↔(3,3) combo=2', 'sliding slide tile=7', 'physics fired @45°', 'pattern correct step 3', 'logic toggle B'. Three orthogonal disciplines visible per frame as concrete dict entries (the 5 PUZZLES rows on the LEFT, dispatch routing through `PUZZLES[active].method(...)` with zero per-genre branching anywhere in the controller's event loop), board values (the MIDDLE-panel grid renders read directly from `match3.grid[r][c]` and `sliding.grid[r][c]` ints — same 2D-array shape across both grid-based genres), and iteration counts (the RIGHT-panel combo counter IS the cascade loop's iteration count without any extra accumulator — `combo = 0; while self.step(): combo += 1` where step() returns True iff the grid changed). Three quiz Qs covering all three axes (B-correct in each per the canonical position): (Q1) polymorphic puzzle-genre dispatch via shared protocol at PUZZLE-GENRE scope (every genre class implements the same handle_click / render / step interface and the controller calls `PUZZLES[active].method(...)` once with no per-genre branching anywhere, so adding a sixth genre word_puzzles = one new class plus one new dict entry with zero edits to the controller's event loop or render orchestrator; same UIElement-protocol pattern from chat-67 graphics_ui_hud and PlatformAdapter pattern from chat-73 publishing_platforms applied at PUZZLE-GENRE scope = SECOND polymorphic-dispatch lesson reinforcing the shared-protocol pattern at a new domain scope; distractor A = dict-lookup-performance anti-model conflating O(1) dispatch cost with the actual architectural driver of controller-code modularity; distractor C = memory-as-driver anti-model treating dict-stored-instance-overhead as the design driver rather than controller-code modularity); (Q2) grid-state-as-2D-array at BOARD-REPRESENTATION scope (match-3 stores its 8×8 board as `grid[r][c] = color_int` with values 0–5 plus −1 for cleared cells and sliding stores its 4×4 board as `grid[r][c] = number` with values 0–15 (0 = empty) — both genres share the same 2D-array shape so swap and slide are both two-line index-pair assignments, win-check is a flat scan, match-detect is two nested for-loops over (r, c), serialization is one `json.dumps` call, and undo is one list-comprehension deep-copy; same data-driven externalization pattern as architecture_save_load schema chat-58 + pathfinding terrain-cost dict chat-60 + behavior-trees child-list-order chat-61 + decision-making personality dict chat-62 + procedural generation seed chat-68 + publishing_executables .spec file chat-70 + publishing_marketing pitch templates chat-71 + publishing_performance algorithmic-axis toggles chat-72 + publishing_platforms TARGETS dict chat-73 + publishing_updates CADENCES + MIGRATIONS dicts chat-74 applied at BOARD-REPRESENTATION scope = **SEVENTEENTH lesson reinforcing data-driven externalization across Phase 8, FIRST applied at BOARD-REPRESENTATION scope** where the board IS the data the puzzle's algorithms (swap, slide, match-detect, cascade) read and mutate; distractor A = parallel-Cell-object-graph anti-model claiming row/col/color attributes plus four neighbor pointers is conceptually cleaner — actually every swap/slide becomes 'rebind two object refs plus update each Cell's row/col fields plus traverse neighbor pointers', save/load needs custom __init__ logic per Cell type, match-detect needs object-identity comparison rather than int equality; distractor C = static-type-safety anti-model claiming plain int values give mypy more information than Cell instances — actually Python is duck-typed and both shapes can be annotated equivalently; the architectural reason is operation-site simplicity, not static type checks); (Q3) match-cascade-as-fixed-point-loop at MATCH-CASCADE scope (match-3's handle_click ends with `combo = 0; while self.step(): combo += 1` where step() is a frozen contract that takes the current grid and produces either a strictly different grid (returns True) or the same grid (returns False); the loop converges because the int-valued grid has finitely many states and clearing strictly reduces the count of marked cells, so the iteration must reach a stable state; the combo multiplier IS the iteration count without any extra accumulator — every True return increments combo by exactly one; same chained-contract pattern as chat-74 publishing_updates' MIGRATIONS dict (each iteration is a frozen contract that may produce a new state requiring another iteration) applied at MATCH-CASCADE scope; distractor A = bounded-MAX_CASCADE_DEPTH anti-model claiming a `for _ in range(MAX_CASCADE_DEPTH): self.step()` loop avoids unbounded-while risk — actually the fixed-point loop terminates exactly when no further matches exist regardless of depth, while a bounded loop caps combo artificially even when more matches exist after the limit AND runs unnecessary iterations on simple swaps where step() returned False after one pass; distractor C = combo-threaded-into-step anti-model claiming the combo counter must be threaded into step() itself — actually the iteration count of the outer while loop already IS the combo, and threading state into step() couples the cascade primitive to its caller's bookkeeping; the clean shape keeps step() focused on grid transitions and lets the outer loop count its own iterations). All three quiz questions used shape-2 outer-single-quote attribute values per chat-57-close codification (`data-correct='false'`/`data-correct='true'` with `&apos;` for embedded apostrophes and `&quot;` for embedded double quotes — **22ND consecutive cohort post-codification chat-54–chat-75**); literal U+2014 em-dash codepoints throughout for the **22ND consecutive chat 54–75 M1**; HTML-escaped `&lt;` (multiple occurrences in comparisons like `0 &lt;= c &lt; 8`, `if 0 &lt;= nr &lt; 8`) and `&gt;` (multiple occurrences in conditions like `if v &gt;= 0`, `if combo &gt; 0`, plus `if len(log) &